  \section{Theory}\label{theory}
  
  \subsection{Exchange effectiveness}\label{exchange-effectiveness}
  
  Sensible heat is defined by the temperature exchange effectiveness, and
  latent heat is defined by the humidity exchange effectiveness. Each flow
  is defined as shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:POL_flow_schematics}. The
  abbreviations are as follows.
  
  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    OA: Outer Air. Air sent from outdoors to the total heat exchanger
  \item
    SA: Supply Air. Air supplied indoors after passing through the total
    heat exchanger
  \item
    RA: Return Air. Air sent from indoors to the total heat exchanger
  \item
    EA: Exhausted Air. Air discharged outdoors after passing through the
    total heat exchanger
  \end{itemize}
  
  \begin{figure}
  \centering
  \pandocbounded{\includegraphics[keepaspectratio,alt={Shematic of a enthalpy exchanger element (corrugate/ cross flow) .}]{C:/Users/Masaya/AppData/Local/Temp/media-d065dc4c146111bc/img/POL_flow_schematics.png}}
  \caption{Shematic of a enthalpy exchanger element (corrugate/ cross
  flow) .}\label{fig:POL_flow_schematics}
  \end{figure}
  
  If temperature is represented by \(T\) and humidity by \(\omega\), the
  corresponding exchange effectiveness values \(\eta_{\mathrm{t}}\) and
  \(\eta_{\mathrm{h}}\) can be expressed as follows.
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:temperature_exchange_eff}{
  \eta_{\mathrm{T}} = \frac{T_{\mathrm{OA}} - T_{\mathrm{SA}}}
  {T_{\mathrm{OA}} - T_{\mathrm{RA}}}
  }\end{equation}
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:humid_exchange_eff}{
  \eta_{\mathrm{\omega}} = \frac{\omega_{\mathrm{OA}} - \omega_{\mathrm{SA}}}
  {\omega_{\mathrm{OA}} - \omega_{\mathrm{RA}}}
  }\end{equation}
  
  \subsection{\texorpdfstring{Representation of moisture flux using
  \(\omega\)}{Representation of moisture flux using \textbackslash omega}}\label{representation-of-moisture-flux-using-omega}
  
  The most important aspect of this analysis is the modeling of moisture
  transport through the membrane. The model described below was developed
  by J.L. Niu and L.Z. Zhang in 2001 {[}1{]} and has continued to be used
  up to the latest paper in 2025 {[}2{]}. In this model, three
  representations of moisture appear: the absolute humidity in air
  \(\omega\), the relative humidity in air \(\phi\), and the absolute
  humidity in the membrane \(\theta\). Their definitions are as follows.
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:def_omega}{
  \omega = \frac{m_{\mathrm{vapor}}}{m_{\mathrm{dry , air}}}
  }\end{equation}
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:def_phi}{
  \phi = \frac{p_{\mathrm{vapor}}}{p_{\mathrm{sat}}}
  }\end{equation}
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:def_theta}{
  \theta = \frac{m_{\mathrm{vapor}}}{m_{\mathrm{dry , membrane}}}
  }\end{equation}
  
  Here, \(m\) denotes mass and \(p\) denotes pressure. In Fluent, the mass
  fraction \(Y\) of each constituent species is generally used. That is,
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:def_Y}{
  Y_{\mathrm{vapor}} = \frac{m_{\mathrm{vapor}}}{m_{\mathrm{dry , air}} + m_{\mathrm{vapor}}}
  }\end{equation} For simplicity, the subscripts vapor, membrane, and air
  are hereafter denoted as v, m, and a, respectively. The absolute
  humidity \(\omega\) and relative humidity \(\phi\) in air, and the
  absolute humidity \(\omega\) and mass fraction \(Y\), can be converted
  using the following equations.
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:p_to_omega}{
  p_{\mathrm{v}} = \frac{\omega p_{\mathrm{tot}}}{\omega + 0.622}
  }\end{equation}
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:phi_to_omega}{
  \begin{aligned}
  \frac{\phi}{\omega} &= A - 1.61\phi \\
  &\approx  A\\
  A &= \exp \left( 5294/T\right) \times 10^{-6}
  \end{aligned}
  }\end{equation}
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:omega_to_Y}{
  \omega = \frac{Y_{\mathrm{v}}}{1-Y_{\mathrm{v}}}
  }\end{equation}
  
  Here, the second term in Eq. Eq.~\ref{eq:phi_to_omega} is 5\% or less
  and is generally neglected {[}1{]}. So far, four representations of
  moisture have appeared. In the field of total heat exchange, it is
  common practice to use \(\omega\). On the other hand, in numerical
  analysis, \(Y\) is often used. As of 2013, there is a statement that
  “moisture transfer in porous media cannot be calculated well. Therefore,
  each researcher develops their own code or runs Fluent using UDFs”
  {[}3{]}. Since moisture transport in the fluid region of a porous medium
  in Fluent, namely simple advection-diffusion of water vapor, appears to
  have already been supported as a standard function at that time, this
  statement is considered to refer to the treatment of water vapor that is
  adsorbed and diffuses in the solid part of the porous material. In
  {[}2{]} as well, it is stated that even in version 2024R1, the mass
  transfer model inside the membrane is not handled, and a UDF was used.
  Therefore, in this chapter, the modeling is first carried out using the
  \(\omega\) representation, and then it is converted into a form using
  \(Y\) in order to make it compatible with Fluent. The following
  assumptions are made for the modeling.
  
  \begin{enumerate}
  \def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
  \item
    Moisture transport in the in-plane flow direction is neglected. This
    is based on the calculation results in reference {[}1{]}. Since this
    assumption may break down depending on the operating conditions, it
    should be confirmed that the Pe number is 2 or larger.
  \item
    Moisture absorption in the membrane is in equilibrium.
  \item
    The moisture diffusion coefficient in the membrane \(D_{\mathrm{m}}\)
    is constant.
  \item
    The heat absorption and heat release during moisture absorption and
    desorption are constant and have the same value.
  \end{enumerate}
  
  First, since moisture absorption in the membrane is in equilibrium, the
  flux from the supply-side air to the membrane \(j_{\mathrm{s}}\), the
  flux inside the membrane \(j_{\mathrm{m}}\), and the flux from the
  membrane to the exhaust-side air \(j_{\mathrm{e}}\) are equal. That is,
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:flux_equ}{
  j_{\mathrm{s}} = j_{\mathrm{m}} = j_{\mathrm{e}}
  }\end{equation}
  
  Here, the unit of flux is \([\mathrm{kg ; m^{-2} ; s^{-1}}]\). The
  moisture fluxes in air, \(j_{\mathrm{s}}\) and \(j_{\mathrm{e}}\), are
  expressed by Fick’s law regardless of whether they are on the intake
  side or the exhaust side. That is,
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:fick_law}{
  j_{\mathrm{s}} =j_{\mathrm{e}} = - \rho_{\mathrm{a}} D_{\mathrm{a}} \frac{\partial \omega}{\partial z}
  }\end{equation}
  
  Here, \(D\) is the diffusion coefficient with respect to \(\omega\)
  {[}\(\mathrm{m^2 ; s^{-1}}\){]}, and it should be noted that it takes a
  different value when converted to \(Y\), as described later. Next,
  consider the flux inside the membrane \(j_{\mathrm{m}}\). To do this, it
  is necessary to obtain the relationship between \(\omega\) in the air
  near the membrane and \(\theta\) at the membrane surface. This
  \(\theta\) strongly depends on the membrane material properties and
  humidity, and must be determined experimentally. For example, an
  analyzer such as a Vapor absorption analyzer - Hydrosorb-1000 {[}4{]}
  can be used. Through this analysis, a sorption curve is obtained. The
  sorption curve takes the relative humidity \(\phi\) on the horizontal
  axis and the absolute humidity of the membrane \(\theta\) on the
  vertical axis, and is expressed by the following equation.
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:sorption_curve}{
  \theta = \frac{w_{\mathrm{max}}}
  {1-C+C/\phi}
  }\end{equation}
  
  Here, \(w_{\mathrm{max}}\) is \(\theta\) when \(\phi\) is 100\%. \(C\)
  is a variable that mainly represents the type of membrane or hygroscopic
  material. For example, the most commonly used silica gel has
  \(C \approx 1\), whereas polymer materials show values of approximately
  \(C \approx 10\). Sorption curves for each value of \(C\) are shown in
  Fig.~\ref{fig:POL_sorption_curve}.
  
  \begin{figure}
  \centering
  \pandocbounded{\includegraphics[keepaspectratio,alt={Sorption curves with representative C numbers.}]{C:/Users/Masaya/AppData/Local/Temp/media-d065dc4c146111bc/img/POL_sorption_curve.png}}
  \caption{Sorption curves with representative \(C\)
  numbers.}\label{fig:POL_sorption_curve}
  \end{figure}
  
  By experimentally determining this sorption curve, \(\theta\) at the
  membrane surface is obtained. When this moisture diffuses through the
  membrane, if the diffusion coefficient of the membrane is denoted by
  \(D_{\mathrm{m}} ; [\mathrm{m^2 ; s^{-1}}]\), the moisture flux inside
  the membrane is expressed as
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:vapor_flux_in_membrane}{
  j_{\mathrm{m}} = - \rho_{\mathrm{m}} D_{\mathrm{m}}\frac{\partial \theta}{\partial z}
  }\end{equation}
  
  For example, the diffusion coefficient of paper is approximately
  \(6 \times 10^{-12} ; \mathrm{m^2 ; s^{-1}}\). Since this equation is
  written in terms of \(\theta\), it must be converted to \(\omega\). For
  this conversion, the membrane resistance \(r_{\mathrm{m}}\), which also
  accounts for the membrane thickness, is expressed as
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:moisture_resistance}{
  r_{\mathrm{m}} =\frac{\rho_{\mathrm{a}}}{\rho_{\mathrm{m}}} \frac{\delta}{D_{\mathrm{m}}} \psi
  }\end{equation}
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:CMDR}{
  \psi = \left(A\frac{\partial \theta}{\partial \phi} \right)^{-1}
  }\end{equation}
  
  Here, the values of \(A\) and \(\phi\) on the supply-air side are used.
  The product \(\rho_{\mathrm{m}}D_{\mathrm{m}}\) is sometimes treated
  collectively as the moisture permeability coefficient
  \(K [\mathrm{kg ; m^{-1} ; s^{-1}}]\). See reference {[}1{]} for
  details. Here, \(\psi\) is called the coefficient of moisture diffusive
  resistance. Using Eq. Eq.~\ref{eq:phi_to_omega}, this CMDR can be
  transformed as
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:CMDR_rev}{
  \begin{aligned}
  \psi &= \left(A\frac{\partial \theta}{\partial \phi} \right)^{-1} \
  &=  \left( A \frac{\partial \theta}{\partial \omega} \frac{\partial \omega}{\partial \phi} \right) ^{-1} \
  &= \left( \frac{\partial \theta}{\partial \omega} \right)^{-1}
  \end{aligned}
  }\end{equation}
  
  Therefore, using Eqs. Eq.~\ref{eq:vapor_flux_in_membrane},
  Eq.~\ref{eq:moisture_resistance}, and Eq.~\ref{eq:CMDR_rev}, the
  moisture flux inside the membrane becomes
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:vapor_flux_in_membrane_rev}{
  j_{\mathrm{m}} = -\frac{\rho_{\mathrm{a}} \delta }{r_{\mathrm{m}}}\frac{\partial \omega}{\partial z}
  }\end{equation} Thus, Eq.~\ref{eq:flux_equ}, Eq.~\ref{eq:fick_law}, and
  Eq.~\ref{eq:vapor_flux_in_membrane_rev} express all moisture fluxes:
  from the supply-side air to the membrane, from the inside of the
  membrane to the outside of the membrane, and from the membrane to the
  exhaust-side air.
  
  By discretizing and solving Eq.~\ref{eq:flux_equ},
  \(\omega_{\mathrm{m}}\) can be expressed only in terms of the air-side
  \(\omega_{\mathrm{a}}\). For the discretization, the following
  subscripts are defined.
  
  \begin{itemize}
  \item
    as: air at supply flow
  \item
    ms: membrane surface at supply side
  \item
    me: membrane surface at exhaust side
  \item
    ae: air at exhaust flow Also, let the distance from the membrane
    surface to the center of the adjacent space cell be \(\Delta z\), and
    let the membrane thickness be \(\delta\). Then,
  \end{itemize}
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:diff_flux_supply}{
  j_{\mathrm{s}} = - \rho_{\mathrm{as}} D_{\mathrm{as}}
  \frac{\omega_{\mathrm{ms}}-\omega_{\mathrm{as}}}{\Delta z_{\mathrm{s}}}
  }\end{equation}
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:diff_flux_membrane}{
  j_{\mathrm{m}} = - \frac{\rho_{\mathrm{as}} \delta }{r_{\mathrm{m}}}
  \frac{\omega_{\mathrm{me}}-\omega_{\mathrm{ms}}}{\delta}
  }\end{equation}
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:diff_flux_exhaust}{
  j_{\mathrm{e}} = - \rho_{\mathrm{ae}} D_{\mathrm{ae}}
  \frac{\omega_{\mathrm{ae}}-\omega_{\mathrm{me}}}{\Delta z_{\mathrm{e}}}
  }\end{equation}
  
  Solving \(j_{\mathrm{s}} + j_{\mathrm{e}} = 0\) and
  \(j_{\mathrm{s}} + j_{\mathrm{m}} = 0\) gives
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:omega_me}{
  \omega_{\mathrm{me}} = \omega_{\mathrm{ae}} + \alpha \left(
  \omega_{\mathrm{as}} - \omega_{\mathrm{ms}}
  \right)\
  \alpha = \frac{\rho_{\mathrm{as}}}{\rho_{\mathrm{ae}}} \frac{D_{\mathrm{as}}}{D_{\mathrm{ae}}} \frac{\Delta z_{\mathrm{ae}}}{\Delta z_{\mathrm{as}}}
  }\end{equation}
  
  and
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:omega_ms}{
  \omega_{\mathrm{ms}} =\frac{
  \beta \omega_{\mathrm{ae}} + (\alpha \beta  + 1)\omega_{\mathrm{as}}
  }{
  \beta + \alpha \beta + 1
  }\
  \beta = \frac{\rho_{\mathrm{m}}}{\rho_{\mathrm{as}}} \frac{D_{\mathrm{m}}}{D_{\mathrm{as}}} \frac{\Delta z_{\mathrm{as}}}{\delta} \frac{1}{\psi}
  }\end{equation}
  
  These two equations allow \(\omega\) at each membrane surface to be
  expressed in terms of the air-side \(\omega\).
  
  \subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{Representation of moisture flux using
  \(Y\)}{Representation of moisture flux using Y}}\label{representation-of-moisture-flux-using-y}
  
  Among the variables introduced so far, the quantities that can be
  treated as constant physical properties are the densities \(\rho\) and
  the diffusion coefficients \(D\). Among these, the diffusion coefficient
  data held in Fluent are based on the mass-fraction gradient. Up to this
  point, Fick’s law has been expressed using \(\omega\) in accordance with
  the convention in the field of heat exchangers. Rewriting it into a form
  compatible with Fluent gives
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:fick_law_in_Y}{
  \begin{aligned}
  j &= - \rho D \frac{\partial \omega}{\partial z}\
  &= - \rho D \frac{\partial Y}{\partial z} \frac{\partial \omega}{\partial Y}\
  &= - \rho \frac{D}{(1-Y)^2} \frac{\partial Y}{\partial z}
  \end{aligned}
  }\end{equation} Thus, if the diffusion coefficient based on \(Y\) is
  denoted by \(D'\), using \(D' = D / (1-Y)^2\) gives
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:fick_law_in_Y_rev}{
  \begin{aligned}
  j = - \rho D' \frac{\partial Y}{\partial z}
  \end{aligned}
  }\end{equation} Therefore, it should be noted that a correction is
  applied between the diffusion coefficient based on the mass fraction
  \(Y\) and that based on the absolute humidity \(\omega\). This
  correction is generally on the order of a few percent. Rewriting Eqs.
  Eq.~\ref{eq:omega_me} and Eq.~\ref{eq:omega_ms} using this diffusion
  coefficient \(D'\) gives
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:Y_me}{
  Y_{\mathrm{me}} = Y_{\mathrm{ae}} + \alpha \left(
  Y_{\mathrm{as}} - Y_{\mathrm{ms}}
  \right)\
  \alpha' = \frac{\rho_{\mathrm{as}}}{\rho_{\mathrm{ae}}} \frac{D'*{\mathrm{as}}}{D'*{\mathrm{ae}}} \frac{\Delta z_{\mathrm{ae}}}{\Delta z_{\mathrm{as}}}
  }\end{equation}
  
  and
  
  \begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq:Y_ms}{
  Y_{\mathrm{ms}} =\frac{
  \beta Y_{\mathrm{ae}} + (\alpha \beta  + 1)Y_{\mathrm{as}}
  }{
  \alpha + \alpha \beta + 1
  }\
  \beta' = \frac{\rho_{\mathrm{m}}}{\rho_{\mathrm{as}}} \frac{D'*{\mathrm{m}}}{D'*{\mathrm{as}}} \frac{\Delta z_{\mathrm{as}}}{\delta} \frac{1}{\psi}
  }\end{equation}
  
  Although the discussion so far has proceeded starting from \(\omega\),
  in general, the \(D'\) used here should be regarded as the physical
  diffusion coefficient data provided. On that basis, if conversion to
  \(\omega\) or other variables is required, the differential coefficients
  should be converted each time.
  
  \subsection{Evaluation of membrane
  performance}\label{evaluation-of-membrane-performance}
  
  Based on the theory above, the physical quantities that must be measured
  for modeling are as follows.
  
  \begin{enumerate}
  \def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
  \item
    Sorption curve: This is the most important curve connecting the
    relative humidity \(\phi\) of the air near the membrane and the
    moisture uptake \(\theta\) inside the membrane. Although the effects
    of temperature and pressure on this curve need to be investigated,
    since \(\phi\) itself has temperature dependence, it is desirable to
    obtain the curve for each operating condition defined in WP1.
  \item
    Moisture diffusion coefficient inside the membrane \(D'*\mathrm{m}\):
    In general, the diffusion coefficient is a function of temperature and
    moisture content, but it is often treated as a constant. The effects
    of temperature and moisture content need to be investigated. If it is
    difficult to measure \(D'_{\mathrm{m}}\) alone, measuring the moisture
    permeability performance of the membrane as a whole is also
    sufficient. Although this probably depends on the measurement method,
    it corresponds to one of \(r_{\mathrm{m}}\), \(r'_{\mathrm{m}}\),
    \(\rho_{\mathrm{m}} D_{\mathrm{m}}\), or
    \(\rho_{\mathrm{m}} D'_{\mathrm{m}}\).
  \item
    Membrane thickness \(\delta\): Since \(\delta\) has a first-order
    effect on \(r_{\mathrm{m}}\), its error directly appears as an error
    in the membrane resistance. \(\delta\) is generally on the order of 10
    μm, so precise measurement is required. In addition, it is necessary
    to confirm how much it changes between the dry and moisture-absorbed
    states.
  \item
    Membrane density \(\rho_{\mathrm{m}}\): The apparent density in the
    dry state is measured. The apparent density includes voids and is
    therefore smaller than the density of the material itself. By
    considering the density of the material itself together with this
    value, the porosity can also be obtained.
  \item
    Thermal conductivity \(k_{\mathrm{m}}\): The thermal conductivity
    representing sensible heat transfer in the membrane is measured.
    However, the importance of this measurement is low. The overall
    thermal resistance accounts for both the heat transfer coefficient
    from the air to the membrane and this thermal conductivity, but in
    general, the effect of the membrane thermal conductivity on the
    overall thermal resistance is small. For example, even changing the
    membrane from paper to metal is said to improve it by only about 5\%.
    Therefore, the dominant factor in sensible heat exchange between
    membranes is the heat transfer coefficient, while the thermal
    conductivity is auxiliary {[}\textbf{undated-uj?}{]}.
  \end{enumerate}
  
